      About this item

      • 2024 PCMag Editor's Choice - Praised for its outstanding value, delivering sharp 2K resolution and a comprehensive feature set.
      • Compact, Versatile, Weatherproof - The Tapo C120 is a compact camera suitable for indoor and outdoor use, featuring an IP66 rating for withstanding rain, dust, and rugged conditions.
      • Magnetic Base for Flexible Mounting - Easily attach the C120 camera to any metal surface with its magnetic base. Versatile mounting on railings, frames, or even the refrigerator.
      • 2K QHD 4MP Resolution - Crystal-clear detail in every shot. Capture every moment with stunning 2K quality that ensures even the finest details are never missed.
      • Starlight Color Night Vision - The built-in Starlight sensor delivers bright, colorful video at night, with two spotlights for extra illumination in darker conditions.
      • Invisible IR Mode - Get night vision up to 30ft with IR light. If the red light is distracting, switch to invisible mode for discreet monitoring.
      • No-Cost Person/Pet/Vehicle Detection - The Tapo C120 uses AI to detect people, pets, or vehicles for free. Customize alerts to focus on specific objects and reduce notifications.
      • Full Duplex 2-Way Audio - Talk in real time, just like a phone call, for smooth communication with delivery personnel, kids, pets, and more.
      • Local or Cloud Storage - Store recordings on a MicroSD card up to 512GB (not included) or via the Tapo Care Cloud subscription. [Check TP-Link FAQ for MicroSD compatibility before purchase.]

          Product Description

          If you are looking for a compact, feature packed, versatile camera solution, the Tapo C120 is the ideal camera for you. The camera includes premium features at no additional cost, such as its free person/pet/vehicle detection, powered by AI processing as well as a suite of other features including full duplex two-way audio, Alexa and Google compatibility and light and sound alarms. Monitor where you want with custom monitoring zones and add additional privacy with privacy zones. The camera image sensor is 1/29.'' progressive scan CMOS starlight sensor. The camera lens focal length is 3.17 mm and has a 1.65 aperture. The camera field of view is 120 diagonal, 103 horizontal, and 55 vertical. The night vision is 850 nm IR LED (30 ft / 9 m), 940 nm IR LED (30 ft / 9 m). The camera has full color night vision. The camera frame rate is 20 fps (self-adaptive according to brightness). The camera's digital zoom is 12x. The camera's video compression is H.264. The camera has a live view. The image enhancement features 3K DNR and WDR. This camera has two-way audio with noise cancellation. The siren level is 96dB (level measured at 4-inch/10-cm distance). This camera's AI detections include motion detection, person detection, line-crossing detection, baby cry detection, vehicle detection, pet detection, meow detection, bark detection, and glass-breaking detection. This camera supports the 802.11b/g/n protocol. The wireless rates are as follows: 11 Mbps (802.11 b), 54 Mbps (802.11 g), 72.2 Mbps (802.11n). Wireless security includes WPA, WPA2-PSK. The security features include 128-bit AES encryption with SSL/TLS and on-device machine learning. The packaging contents include 1 Tapo C120 Camera, 1 5.0 V, 1.0 A power adapter, 3m (9.84ft) Type-C wire, 4 mounting anchors, 4 mounting screws, 2 cable organizers, 1 mounting template, 1 iron camera base, 3M adhesive, detaching pin, 1 quick start guide.

          Amazon Customer
          4 out of 5 stars
          Best in Class, but...
          The performance is as good as PC Mag reported. It works with NVRs and Blue Iris, and no subscription is required. The form factor is almost as small as the Wyze Cam V3, but without being forever trapped within the Wyze ecosystem, which does not support any security hardware or software other than their own inbred solutions. The audio from Tapo's built in microphone is good enough to actually use and under ideal lighting conditions, the video can look as good as that from multi-hundred-dollar professional cameras.With that said, while I do genuinely appreciate the fact that it is usable with NVRs / Blue Iris, the configuration process is arcane. The camera has no built-in web GUI, so all administration must be done via mobile app. It "works", but is clumsy, arcane, and quite limited compared to a real web GUI. Not that I've seen any other camera in this price class that is any better in this regard...it's just that Tapo came so close to greatness!The build is functional and even attractive, in a certain way, but is entirely plastic. I'm sure I could wreck it with two fingers. But it's also quite light, so if kept out of harm's way, may hold up for a while. There is no way to get portrait or "corridor" mode with a ceiling mount. It would be possible with a wall mount, although somewhat awkward-looking. And while Blue Iris allows camera rotation in 90 degree increments, the Tapo mobile app provides only an "invert image" option.Be aware that if you want to use this camera without a subscription and without an NVR, you're going to need a micoSD card, and if you want enough storage for 30 days of continuous recording, it's going to cost you double the price of the camera itself. For every camera. This is a fallacy of distributed storage. And since SD card makers are reticent to publish meaningful durability specs, there is no way to predict how long that expensive storage will survive. That, and if a bad actor should swipe your camera, the recording of the deed will be gone as well. Since the C120 has no web GUI, unless one is using Blue Iris, it is not possible to monitor live video using a real computer, short of awkward use with third party software such as VLC.If you plan to use the camera with Blue Iris, then you won't care about SD card problems, but you will care about how arcane the setup process is. You'll also care that there may be no way to firewall the camera from the internet without also breaking the mobile app, which is, again, the only way to administer the camera.And one more limitation that can be more challenging than one might imagine - there is no way to change or even replace the supplied power cable. It has a USB-C connector on the camera end, which at first seems somewhat universal, but no - take a look at the attached photo. The one on the left is advertised as working with the C120. The cable that comes with the C121 (the black version of the same camera) is on the one on the right. Notice the notched shoulder around the perimeter of the connector, , which exactly fits within the rubber grommet on the camera. The white one won't even make contact. Nobody is talking about this, but I think it's a big deal. I asked Tapo for help, but they gave me none. They were unwilling/unable even to sell or provide a replacement identical to the original cable, let alone a longer one.3 meters is not long enough for most mounting locations, and there is no way to get a longer cable. For that matter, if the original cable fails, the camera will become entirely useless. Ridiculous. Maybe one could hack out the rubber boot, but then the camera would no longer be water resistant. A frustrating example of planned obsolescence. Or perhaps, just very bad planning. If it was an Apple device, they'd make it where only their own cables would work, and then sell the cables for $50 each. At the very least, Tapo is missing an opportunity. For that matter, while USB-C may be all the rage these days, it has significant length limitations. By comparison, a more traditional coaxial power connector would make it possible to accommodate a wide range of connector styles, since the OD of the connector barrel remains constant across all styles. In addition, simple 2-conductor cable is physically smaller, less conspicuous, less expensive, and works fine at much greater lengths. And a smaller round connector is easier to poke through holes for more elegant/permanent installations.Of course, Tapo could solve this problem, and more, by providing a PoE option. It would be great to be able to have a hardwired network option, and PoE is such a great way to power a camera, providing a safe power supply with virtually unlimited length and routing options. As opposed to having janky extension cords (and the camera's power supply brick), outside in the weather. Because, again, the provided cable is only 10-feet long. And the included power supply is not protected against the weather. It's either that, or mount the camera outside, close enough to a window to run the short power cable in though the window. Which may then damage the non-replaceable cable. And even if one manages to get the power brick inside, the chances of an outlet being near enough are next to none.This is Tapo's Achilles heal. There is no elegant way to power the camera at outdoor locations that might otherwise be the most ideal. Assuming, of course, that one has adequate Wi-Fi coverage outside, where the camera(s) need to be. PoE would solve both problems.Until such time if/when TP-Link addresses these issues, the C120 is best-suited to indoor use, or to very fortunate/clever outdoor installations. Maybe mount them inside of windows, with the understanding that the on-camera illuminators will be made useless by the glass. The Starlight sensor is pretty good, to a point, but reflections from indoor lights can be crippling, and in any case, one would need some outdoor lighting in order to get useful nighttime video.

            These maintain a solid WiFi connection with decent, though not fantastic, image quality. They are also compatible with 3rd party NAS devices by IP, which is a definite plus.
